title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>It is useful to draw horizontal and vertical lines (either dashed or slid, it makes no difference except for typography), to partition a matrix into blocks, permitting us to write
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \left [     \begin {array}{c:c}         \mathbf {B} & \mathbf {C} \\ \hdashline          \mathbf {D} & \mathbf {E}      \end {array} \right ] = \left [     \begin {array}{c|c}         \mathbf {B} & \mathbf {C} \\ \hline          \mathbf {D} & \mathbf {E}      \end {array} \right ].]]></fr:tex>
We could partition a matrix however we want, and we call the blocks <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Submatrices</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>. Writing <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> in this manner is called a <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Block Decomposition</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:tree
