text="Matrix">Matrix</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> be positive integers. We define an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex>-by-<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Matrix</html:dfn> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> to be a rectangular array of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[mn]]></fr:tex> real [or complex] numbers arranged in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> horizontal <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Rows</html:dfn> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> vertical <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Columns</html:dfn>, written:
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \left (\begin {array}{cccccc}   a_{11} & a_{12} & … & a_{1j} & … & a_{1n} \\ a_{21} & a_{22} & … & a_{2j} & … & a_{2n}  \\ \vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\ a_{i1} & a_{i2} & … & a_{ij} & … & a_{in} \\ \vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\ a_{m1} & a_{m2} & …   & a_{mj} & …  & a_{mn}  \end {array}\right ) \begin {array}{c}   \\   \gets  i^{\text {th}}\hbox {\ row} \end {array}]]></fr:tex>
We have highlighted the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i^{\text {th}}]]></fr:tex> row, and the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[j^{\text {th}}]]></fr:tex> column.</fr:p><fr:p>If further <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m=n]]></fr:tex> (so we have an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-by-<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> matrix), then we call it a <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Square Matrix</html:dfn>. In this case, we can refer to the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Main Diagonal</html:dfn> as the components <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{1,1}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{2,2}]]></fr:tex>, …, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n,n}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>We abbreviate "<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex>-by-<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> matrix" as "<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix". The pair of numbers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(m,n)]]></fr:tex> is called the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Dimensions</html:dfn> of the matrix. (We can also extend our definitions to allow <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> to be zero, but these are degenerate edgecases.)</fr:p><fr:p>Also note, some people use parentheses in writing matrices, other people use square brackets. Both are acceptable.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
