title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>For any positive integer <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, we have the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times  n]]></fr:tex> <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Identity Matrix</html:dfn> to be
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbf {I}_{n} = (\delta _{i,j}) = \begin {cases}1 &\hbox {if }i=j,\\     0 &\hbox {if }i\neq  j   \end {cases}]]></fr:tex>
where the components <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta _{i,j}]]></fr:tex> are referred to as the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Kronecker Delta</html:dfn>.</fr:p><fr:p>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is clear from context, we may suppress the subscript and write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {I}]]></fr:tex> instead of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {I}_{n}]]></fr:tex>. Some authors write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {1}]]></fr:tex> for the identity matrix, because (as we will see) it is analogous to the number <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1\in \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
