title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Column Vector</html:dfn> refers to an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\times 1]]></fr:tex> matrix.</fr:p><fr:p>A <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Row Vector</html:dfn> refers to a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1\times  m]]></fr:tex> matrix.</fr:p><fr:p>A <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Vector</html:dfn> may refer to either row vectors or column vectors; in these notes on elementary linear algebra, we will reserve the word "vector" specifically for "column vector".</fr:p><fr:p>Also note: it is common convention to use superscript indices for column vectors, and subscript indices for row vectors. This allows for the Einstein summation convention to do some stuff automatically for us.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
