display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{i,j}=0]]></fr:tex> when <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[i\neq  j]]></fr:tex> is called a <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Diagonal Matrix</html:dfn>. We may write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}=\mathrm {diag}(a_{1,1}, a_{2,2},…, a_{n,n})]]></fr:tex> to indicate <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> is a diagonal matrix.</fr:p><fr:p>Caution: some authors write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {diag}(\mathbf {A})]]></fr:tex> to refer to the <fr:em>diagonal components</fr:em> of any matrix <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>. Just bear this in mind when you run into it "in the wild".</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
