title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:ol><fr:li>Will every matrix <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>? (Mathematicians call this property "reflexivity", and most "equality-like" relations should have it.)</fr:li>
<fr:li>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex>, is it true or false that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {B} = \mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>? Prove it or find a counter-example.</fr:li>
<fr:li>If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {B} = \mathbf {C}]]></fr:tex>, is it true or false that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {C}]]></fr:tex>? Prove it or find a counter-example. These first three properties are true for 'equivalence relations' (binary relations which loosely resemble equality).</fr:li>
<fr:li>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\neq  p]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix, and if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0\times  p]]></fr:tex> matrix, then is it true or false that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}=\mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex>?</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
